change for us, I think,

00:47:51.700 --> 00:47:55.500
was not only having Evie and Cathy
as editors but Evie being able

00:47:55.500 --> 00:47:58.120
to access the list of [inaudible].

00:47:58.120 --> 00:48:02.200
But I think there's larger sort
of or deeper issues that writers

00:48:02.200 --> 00:48:06.770
of color and what editors of color
and white editors face in trying

00:48:06.770 --> 00:48:08.450
to do the best possible job

00:48:08.450 --> 00:48:11.530
of representing the widest
possible community of poets.

00:48:11.530 --> 00:48:15.970
I think you can talk about that.

00:48:18.790 --> 00:48:21.290
&gt;&gt; Evie Shockley: I'll say
quickly that I mean one

00:48:21.290 --> 00:48:27.490
of the things I think is implied
in your question but that I'd

00:48:27.490 --> 00:48:31.660
like to sort of say out
loud is that we're talking

00:48:31.660 --> 00:48:35.350
about publishing poems about race.

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:42.300
Part of what is just as important
as publishing poets of color,

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:44.260
whether they're talking
about race or not, right?

00:48:44.260 --> 00:48:45.560
&gt;&gt; Cathy Park Hong: Yes.

00:48:45.560 --> 00:48:46.860
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: Yes.

00:48:46.860 --> 00:48:50.750
&gt;&gt; Evie Shockley: And it's -- I
think in some ways it's that moment

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:57.040
that you're able to create enough
of a space in a particular journal

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:01.640
or publishing a, you know, poetry
series or whatever it might be.

00:49:01.640 --> 00:49:04.800
You create enough of a space
where poets don't feel either

00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:12.380
like they're -- maybe a politicized
aesthetic around race is unwelcome,

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:17.560
nor that that's the only way that
they can, you know, get in, is by,

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:21.410
you know, sort of proclaiming
something that's identity-based

00:49:21.410 --> 00:49:25.030
or critique or protest-based.

00:49:25.030 --> 00:49:28.240
That's part of the work that, you
know, that we were trying to do

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:32.940
and that I know that everyone
up here is trying to do.

00:49:32.940 --> 00:49:36.840
And that's what -- that's
what makes the sea change,

00:49:36.840 --> 00:49:40.970
is that you got people
feeling called

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:43.670
by what they are in
the sea [inaudible].

00:49:43.670 --> 00:49:46.740
So the hard part is getting
over that initial tipping point.

00:49:46.740 --> 00:49:52.420
And that is where you have
to go door to door I think.

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:54.850
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: And I'll just
say I think that's true,

00:49:54.850 --> 00:49:59.280
the point you raised for editors
of color, that you shouldn't be --

00:49:59.280 --> 00:50:05.000
there wasn't -- there wasn't I
think [inaudible] editor previous.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:08.770
You know, this sense [inaudible]
not promote this as, okay,

00:50:08.770 --> 00:50:10.330
now you're an editor of color.

00:50:10.330 --> 00:50:12.000
You must only publish
writers of color.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:13.300
That's why you're here.

00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:15.720
That's -- there are those
assumptions of all sides in terms

00:50:15.720 --> 00:50:18.620
of how you have to
negotiate expectations

00:50:18.620 --> 00:50:20.920
for cultural assumptions.

00:50:23.370 --> 00:50:25.200
Don, you want to talk a
little bit about what it's

00:50:25.200 --> 00:50:28.550
like to [inaudible] poetry
and the challenges of that?

00:50:28.550 --> 00:50:30.190
&gt;&gt; Don Share: Yeah.

00:50:30.190 --> 00:50:31.490
Well, I don't know.

00:50:31.490 --> 00:50:32.790
I don't think about how I feel.

00:50:32.790 --> 00:50:34.880
I often think about
how the world is.

00:50:34.880 --> 00:50:37.630
I mean going back to what I
think we've all been saying

00:50:37.630 --> 00:50:44.240
in not the same ways, but
related ways, if you look around

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:47.640 position:56%
and your literature, your art, your
music isn't reflecting what you know

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:52.270
to be true, whatever you might --
whoever you might want to vote for,

00:50:52.270 --> 00:50:56.110
there's something wrong
with your culture.

00:50:56.110 --> 00:50:59.770
And so, I think a lot
of poets that I talk

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:03.070
to about these things actually
didn't set out to write

00:51:03.070 --> 00:51:06.230
about terrible things
happening in the news.

00:51:06.230 --> 00:51:08.940
But when they happen,
they are called upon.

00:51:08.940 --> 00:51:10.940
And they will say something.

00:51:10.940 --> 00:51:17.660 position:56%
I think, you know, you know, there's
really no other way to respond

00:51:17.660 --> 00:51:26.320 position:56%
to it, other than to sort of measure
poetry against what we know to be,

00:51:26.320 --> 00:51:31.150
you know, the feelings and
atmospheres that we all live

00:51:31.150 --> 00:51:34.940
and breathe and eat
and walk around in.

00:51:34.940 --> 00:51:37.570
I mean -- I mean everybody knows
things, but they don't want to --

00:51:37.570 --> 00:51:39.070
you know, there are things that
are hard for people to admit.

00:51:39.070 --> 00:51:42.500
There are things that are
hard for people to concede.

00:51:42.500 --> 00:51:44.990
There are problems
that are hard to --

00:51:44.990 --> 00:51:47.360
you know, and failures
that are hard to own up to.

00:51:47.360 --> 00:51:50.500
And the poets aren't breaking
the [inaudible] so much.

00:51:50.500 --> 00:51:54.270
If they have been called
upon to say things

00:51:54.270 --> 00:51:57.530
that maybe haven't been said
before or hadn't been put in front

00:51:57.530 --> 00:52:00.400
of an audience before, maybe
they have their own way of saying

00:52:00.400 --> 00:52:02.200
about all these things together.

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:08.640 position:56%
But there's a sort of startling
reality about conversations relating

00:52:08.640 --> 00:52:15.480
to race that's interesting
to me because my grandparents

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:18.580
on one side -- great-grandparents
on the other were stateless people

00:52:18.580 --> 00:52:20.960
who came here as immigrants
and didn't speak English,

00:52:20.960 --> 00:52:26.110
and I'm the first person in my
family to be called a white person.

00:52:26.110 --> 00:52:30.870 position:56%
My brother couldn't get into an Ivy
League school because of the quotas.

00:52:30.870 --> 00:52:34.300
My father couldn't be a
doctor for the same reason.

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:37.040
And I grew up in a bilingual
household, I mean the whole thing.

00:52:37.040 --> 00:52:42.120
And my family now has black people,
white people, trans people in it.

00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:45.140
I'm an American, about
as ordinary as can be.

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:48.100
And when I look around or even
when I hear what's going on,

00:52:48.100 --> 00:52:51.750
it's astounding to me how
much in denial people are

00:52:51.750 --> 00:52:54.000
because what is a white person?

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.320
Who are the people who are here,
and where did they come from?

00:52:56.320 --> 00:52:57.620
How did they get here?

00:52:57.620 --> 00:53:00.120
And what did their ancestors do?

00:53:00.120 --> 00:53:04.700
So for me, you're just seeing
the shift that say 100,

00:53:04.700 --> 00:53:07.690
125 years ago people assimilated

00:53:07.690 --> 00:53:10.790
because it was a dream,
the American dream.

00:53:10.790 --> 00:53:14.390
You know, now we know more about
this dream and what it means,

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:19.020
day to day, minute to minute
for people who can't access it.

00:53:19.020 --> 00:53:21.900
So now we have to think
about our dreams differently.

00:53:21.900 --> 00:53:24.040
And that's what we need to
count on the poets to do.

00:53:24.040 --> 00:53:26.390
And they're doing it, you know?

00:53:26.390 --> 00:53:28.730
So it's not just like
there's a group

00:53:28.730 --> 00:53:30.110
and then there's another group.

00:53:30.110 --> 00:53:32.210 position:56%
I mean, you know, you run into this.

00:53:32.210 --> 00:53:35.810
How do you, you know, want
to start classifying anybody,

00:53:35.810 --> 00:53:37.750
whatever the terminology is?

00:53:37.750 --> 00:53:40.340
It's very tricky because
in the end it can't be done

00:53:40.340 --> 00:53:44.610
without dehumanizing people
or corralling sort of a group

00:53:44.610 --> 00:53:47.900
of what are in the end
prejudices or stereotypes

00:53:47.900 --> 00:53:49.970
or sort of group thinking.

00:53:49.970 --> 00:53:51.710
And I think poetry has figured out.

00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:53.830
Like, they have sorted
out a lot of this stuff.

00:53:53.830 --> 00:53:57.750
And what we look around the
nation and the world and see is

00:53:57.750 --> 00:54:01.230
that our politicians and people
out there haven't got it yet.

00:54:01.230 --> 00:54:04.920
They haven't figured out how to
cope with different things yet.

00:54:04.920 --> 00:54:09.370
They haven't been able to describe
what it's like to have conflict,

00:54:09.370 --> 00:54:12.840
not only to be in conflict and
experience conflict, but to be made

00:54:12.840 --> 00:54:16.550
up of conflictive kinds of
things in your background.

00:54:16.550 --> 00:54:20.040
And I think again my belief in
poetry, which I've come by sort

00:54:20.040 --> 00:54:23.470 position:56%
of empirically not because I have
some ideology about it or, you know,

00:54:23.470 --> 00:54:26.570
fantasy about it, but I think
the reality is, is you can --

00:54:26.570 --> 00:54:29.190
these poets that we're
talking about are so good,

00:54:29.190 --> 00:54:31.220
and the world is looking
to us for this.

00:54:31.220 --> 00:54:33.980
What we need is for a lot
of people to sort of come

00:54:33.980 --> 00:54:36.830
on board too and figure out how -

00:54:36.830 --> 00:54:38.940
you know, what is a
national discussion

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:43.390
or international discussion of
conflict and pain and violence

00:54:43.390 --> 00:54:44.870
and equality going to be like?

00:54:44.870 --> 00:54:48.430
And the poets have got
-- are getting at it.

00:54:48.430 --> 00:54:51.470
But the rest of the culture has
other things operating in it

00:54:51.470 --> 00:54:55.000
that make it harder to value
the kind of work that we do.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:59.340
But I do think that's changing
because I think it's hard

00:54:59.340 --> 00:55:03.140
if you're an editor to really see
this, but like Poetry Magazine,

00:55:03.140 --> 00:55:05.030
most of the people who
read it are not poets.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:06.330
They're not other poets.

00:55:06.330 --> 00:55:08.030
You often hear that poetry
is written for other poets.

00:55:08.030 --> 00:55:10.730
Most of my readers
are general readers.

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:12.430
And they may hate or love

00:55:12.430 --> 00:55:15.300
or whatever what they
see, but they get it.

00:55:15.300 --> 00:55:16.600
They understand it.

00:55:16.600 --> 00:55:20.770
And they're -- there is
resistance, and resistance is good

00:55:20.770 --> 00:55:23.890
because it lays out for us the
work that needs to be done.

00:55:27.240 --> 00:55:28.540
&gt;&gt; Cathy Park Hong: I
think it's [inaudible].

00:55:28.540 --> 00:55:32.890
Like, it's not just a question of
diversity and having more poets.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:34.620
I mean it's not just like, okay,

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:39.030
let's have more poems
that address race.

00:55:39.030 --> 00:55:42.480
It's also kind of changing
our assumptions

00:55:42.480 --> 00:55:46.920
about what a race poem is or what
a poet of color should write.

00:55:46.920 --> 00:55:50.350
And I think that Noemi
Press is really doing it.

00:55:50.350 --> 00:55:53.220
And I mean that's what we
were trying to do at jubilat.

00:55:53.220 --> 00:55:58.340
jubilat is amazing how open
[inaudible] has been transformed.

00:55:58.340 --> 00:56:01.910
But I do think that, you know,

00:56:01.910 --> 00:56:05.590
poetry is still very
much an institution

00:56:05.590 --> 00:56:07.600
where -- not Poetry Magazine --

00:56:07.600 --> 00:56:08.900
&gt;&gt; Don Share: Right, right, right.

00:56:08.900 --> 00:56:10.200
[ Laughter ]

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:11.610
&gt;&gt; Cathy Park Hong:
It's [inaudible].

00:56:11.610 --> 00:56:12.910
&gt;&gt; Don Share: Yeah.

00:56:12.910 --> 00:56:16.220
&gt;&gt; Cathy Park Hong: But I think
that it's also important, you know,

00:56:16.220 --> 00:56:19.170
to be aware that I still
feel like a gatekeeper,

00:56:19.170 --> 00:56:22.270
even though I'm someone of color.

00:56:22.270 --> 00:56:23.570 position:56%
I'm still -- I'm still a gatekeeper.

00:56:23.570 --> 00:56:26.020
And that's something
that I acknowledge.

00:56:26.020 --> 00:56:29.180
I do think that, you
know, we're thinking

00:56:29.180 --> 00:56:31.720
about say prizes and so forth.

00:56:31.720 --> 00:56:34.370
And there's still an
expectation on the kind

00:56:34.370 --> 00:56:38.200
of race poem that's accepted
versus the kind of race poem

00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:40.970
that either baffles you
or you're just like --

00:56:40.970 --> 00:56:44.860
you don't understand it, or it's
a poem that has nothing to do

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:46.630
with race, but it's
written by a poet of color.

00:56:46.630 --> 00:56:51.710
And I think a lot of the problem
is not just having more race poems

00:56:51.710 --> 00:56:54.470
in there, but it's also
the fact that a lot

00:56:54.470 --> 00:56:57.790
of times you have a
single frame of reference

00:56:57.790 --> 00:57:00.620
for what a race poem should be.

00:57:00.620 --> 00:57:06.170
And it's really important to
broaden that frame of reference.

00:57:06.170 --> 00:57:09.420
You know, I think [inaudible]
an article where there was like,

00:57:09.420 --> 00:57:12.470
you know, I think a lot of
marginalized groups get plagued

00:57:12.470 --> 00:57:15.980
by this, where there's always
a simple story, you know,

00:57:15.980 --> 00:57:18.240
which is like the single
immigrant story,

00:57:18.240 --> 00:57:20.490
the single black story,
the single Asian story.

00:57:20.490 --> 00:57:24.040
And everyone wants you to
kind of fit in that template.

00:57:24.040 --> 00:57:29.610
And I see that happening a lot of
times, where the kind of attention

00:57:29.610 --> 00:57:32.540
that the books get is that
they fit that template.

00:57:32.540 --> 00:57:34.760
So it's really important.

00:57:34.760 --> 00:57:38.760
So it's not just a -- I think
it's just also just, you know,

00:57:38.760 --> 00:57:42.070
broaden not just the
voices, not this --

00:57:42.070 --> 00:57:46.130
the kind of [inaudible] diversity,
but also changing the way we think

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:47.490
about what our assumptions as well.

00:57:47.490 --> 00:57:50.390
&gt;&gt; Carmen Gimenez Smith: I
would add too that I think

00:57:50.390 --> 00:57:55.280 position:56%
that this historical moment has been
anticipated for many years in terms

00:57:55.280 --> 00:57:57.480
of how we navigate rhetoric.

00:57:57.480 --> 00:58:00.980
And we've become -- as a culture,
we've become so dichotomized

00:58:00.980 --> 00:58:04.360
and so convinced of
our own infallibility.

00:58:04.360 --> 00:58:08.850
But poetry demands that
we engage with nuance

00:58:08.850 --> 00:58:12.750
and we engage with paradox.

00:58:12.750 --> 00:58:15.430
And I think that's just
another really interesting way

00:58:15.430 --> 00:58:19.130
in which poetry is
poised to be a place

00:58:19.130 --> 00:58:20.710
where these conversations
are inevitable

00:58:20.710 --> 00:58:22.660
because we're not writing.

00:58:22.660 --> 00:58:24.120
We're not writing a list of goals,

00:58:24.120 --> 00:58:28.280
and we're not writing op ed
positions, which again, you know,

00:58:28.280 --> 00:58:32.080
I remember Deborah Tannen many,
many -- that book -- I don't --

00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:33.510
I don't remember what it's called.

00:58:33.510 --> 00:58:34.960
"You Just" -- not "You
Just Don't Understand",

00:58:34.960 --> 00:58:37.020
but I think it was called "The
Argument Culture" I think.

00:58:37.020 --> 00:58:39.650 position:56%
And she talked about the experience.

00:58:39.650 --> 00:58:42.180
And I'll never forget this
because when I was reading it,

00:58:42.180 --> 00:58:43.530
this was like 15 years ago.

00:58:43.530 --> 00:58:46.180
I thought, well, this seems a
little alarmist, where she talked

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:49.910
about how she was invited
to a talk show, and what --

00:58:49.910 --> 00:58:52.660
as a linguist, you know, as a
scholar, she expected it to be,

00:58:52.660 --> 00:58:54.080
you know, a conversation.

00:58:54.080 --> 00:58:57.370
But it ended up them saying, "We
want you to have this position,

00:58:57.370 --> 00:58:58.880
and then we're going
to bring in this person

00:58:58.880 --> 00:59:01.970
to have this opposite
reaction to your position."

00:59:01.970 --> 00:59:06.530
And that's not -- that's
not a productive way

00:59:06.530 --> 00:59:09.750
to approach the world, and it
ends up being a very dangerous way

00:59:09.750 --> 00:59:14.690
to approach the world because most
of us don't live on these ends.

00:59:14.690 --> 00:59:16.650
Most of us live in the middle.

00:59:16.650 --> 00:59:21.010
And so, I think that's
part of the reason

00:59:21.010 --> 00:59:23.820
that poetry is having
this moment right now,

00:59:23.820 --> 00:59:26.430
is that there aren't too
many places in the world

00:59:26.430 --> 00:59:31.510
where we can have engaged, complex
conversations about these subjects.

00:59:31.510 --> 00:59:35.250
And so, my hope is
-- and I'm, you know,

00:59:35.250 --> 00:59:37.380
hearing that your sense
of general audience.

00:59:37.380 --> 00:59:41.830
My hope is that poetry
infects all discourses,

00:59:41.830 --> 00:59:46.690
and we start having more robust and
complex conversations because I --

00:59:46.690 --> 00:59:52.150
these dichotomies terrify me
because they leave most people out,

00:59:52.150 --> 00:59:55.900
except people who are shouting
the loudest at either end.

00:59:55.900 --> 00:59:59.800
And that silences a lot of people.

01:00:01.030 --> 01:00:02.580
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: I'm going
to open it up to questions.

01:00:02.580 --> 01:00:04.200
Let me just bring the mic to you

01:00:04.200 --> 01:00:07.040
so that we can make sure
[inaudible] question.

01:00:12.060 --> 01:00:14.180
&gt;&gt; Female Speaker: Well, the
question that first comes

01:00:14.180 --> 01:00:18.960
to my mind is that is
there any time in which any

01:00:18.960 --> 01:00:25.420
of us express ourselves either
verbally or with physical movement

01:00:25.420 --> 01:00:30.100
or anything else in which
race is not being expressed?

01:00:38.100 --> 01:00:40.320
&gt;&gt; Evie Shockley: I
understand the sort

01:00:40.320 --> 01:00:43.130
of the spirit behind your
question, and I think you're right

01:00:43.130 --> 01:00:47.800
that because we live in a society
that's grounded in racial ideology,

01:00:47.800 --> 01:00:54.830
was founded on it, could not exist
as we know it without the history

01:00:54.830 --> 01:00:59.040 position:56%
that it's based in, in race, racism.

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:04.190
At any point, we are all speaking
from a racialized position

01:01:04.190 --> 01:01:08.570
and that it's going
to have an impact.

01:01:08.570 --> 01:01:10.450
It's going to inform what
we saw or what we do.

01:01:10.450 --> 01:01:18.390
And it's going to inform how people
hear us on the other side, right?

01:01:18.390 --> 01:01:24.040
So I think I would point to what
Carmen was saying about a spectrum.

01:01:24.040 --> 01:01:30.530
I mean there are times
when race is not the thing

01:01:30.530 --> 01:01:34.730
that a person is trying to express,
even if they're expressing it

01:01:34.730 --> 01:01:40.700
from a position that is located
on a racialized landscape.

01:01:40.700 --> 01:01:46.980
Maybe the part of what we're
thinking about together then is how

01:01:46.980 --> 01:01:54.950
to -- how to ensure that the way
that landscape gets represented

01:01:54.950 --> 01:01:59.660
in the journals, in the poetry
that's published, how to make sure

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:01.870
that landscape is represented
in its fullest.

01:02:01.870 --> 01:02:07.080
So I hope that gets
at your question.

01:02:07.080 --> 01:02:09.800
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: I will also
say too that to sort of follow

01:02:09.800 --> 01:02:12.570
up on what Cathy was talking about,
I do feel like there are a lot

01:02:12.570 --> 01:02:15.250
of poets of color writing poems
that aren't -- that aren't, quote,

01:02:15.250 --> 01:02:20.310
unquote, race poems, that
there's a place for that

01:02:20.310 --> 01:02:22.160
in the sort of poetry landscape.

01:02:22.160 --> 01:02:25.090
And I think that has
much to do with the --

01:02:25.090 --> 01:02:26.670
not only the writers
writing that work,

01:02:26.670 --> 01:02:29.040
but the publishers
championing that work.

01:02:29.040 --> 01:02:30.340
That's really important.

01:02:30.340 --> 01:02:38.810 position:56%
It sort of goes to that question
because if we assume that, you know,

01:02:38.810 --> 01:02:42.980
an African American writer can
only write about one kind of way

01:02:42.980 --> 01:02:44.760
of seeing true race, it's
a very [inaudible] sort

01:02:44.760 --> 01:02:50.160 position:56%
of [inaudible] thinking and poems
we've discussed kind of problematize

01:02:50.160 --> 01:02:52.840
that in all sorts of wonderful
ways and all sorts of positions.

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:54.140
But they do operate from
an eye that can be kind

01:02:54.140 --> 01:02:55.440
of an empathetic eye too
[inaudible] trained to.

01:02:55.440 --> 01:02:57.850
&gt;&gt; Carmen Gimenez Smith: I
think that the other piece

01:02:57.850 --> 01:03:00.820
of that question, which
I think is so important,

01:03:00.820 --> 01:03:06.210
is that even when race
doesn't feel --

01:03:06.210 --> 01:03:10.460
feels neutral, it's still activated
in any -- in any engagement,

01:03:10.460 --> 01:03:14.410
in any conversation, in
any exchange we have.

01:03:14.410 --> 01:03:16.260
And it's so pervasive.

01:03:16.260 --> 01:03:19.080
It's so pervasive that
we have trained ourselves

01:03:19.080 --> 01:03:20.380
to take it for granted.

01:03:20.380 --> 01:03:26.490
And as a -- as a poet
and thinking about how --

01:03:26.490 --> 01:03:29.270
when let's I -- I'm also a teacher.

01:03:29.270 --> 01:03:34.290 position:56%
I teach a person of color, and I get
a sense of a student saying, "Well,

01:03:34.290 --> 01:03:38.790
I have no use for this
because this is not my race.

01:03:38.790 --> 01:03:40.100
So thank you."

01:03:40.100 --> 01:03:44.570
But the reality is that
the same factors that,

01:03:44.570 --> 01:03:46.590
even though let's say this
student is saying I'm --

01:03:46.590 --> 01:03:50.560
this is a book by a black poet,
and I understand and I sympathize

01:03:50.560 --> 01:03:54.950
and I feel the pain and suffering,

01:03:54.950 --> 01:04:01.740
that in fact this same exact system
that's oppressing the black writer

01:04:01.740 --> 01:04:05.460
writing about their question is
also oppressing this white person.

01:04:05.460 --> 01:04:07.470
They just aren't aware of it.

01:04:07.470 --> 01:04:11.920
They're just not aware that this
is a very huge system designed

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:17.440
to occlude the class
discrepancies that are growing

01:04:17.440 --> 01:04:20.950
in the United States and the
ways in which our participation

01:04:20.950 --> 01:04:23.880 position:56%
and horizontal oppression keep those

01:04:23.880 --> 01:04:28.160
with really the most
money in control.

01:04:28.160 --> 01:04:34.400
And so, I think that race
that we participate in,

01:04:34.400 --> 01:04:38.190
race's role as a straw
man discussion,

01:04:38.190 --> 01:04:42.160
when really it's economic and
equities that's keeping us --

01:04:42.160 --> 01:04:45.710
that's keeping us in many of
these problematic positions.

01:04:45.710 --> 01:04:51.700
And so, I think that reading
all texts and through the lens

01:04:51.700 --> 01:04:56.340
of race is useful now,
regardless of who's writing them,

01:04:56.340 --> 01:05:01.290
because race is this huge
edifice that's -- I don't know.

01:05:01.290 --> 01:05:02.970 position:56%
I think that it's -- I think it's --

01:05:02.970 --> 01:05:06.080
I think we're looking
at the wrong thing,

01:05:06.080 --> 01:05:08.960
even though race is really
relevant and important, and it's --

01:05:08.960 --> 01:05:12.060
and it's sort of inexcusable
not to be thinking about it.

01:05:12.060 --> 01:05:15.840
I also think that there are many
layers to how we navigate it.

01:05:15.840 --> 01:05:19.260
And class is a much bigger,
much more potent one.

01:05:19.260 --> 01:05:21.440
And we're working against
each other.

01:05:21.440 --> 01:05:25.070
We're really fighting against each
other when there's a much larger,

01:05:25.070 --> 01:05:28.440
more ominous and dangerous force
that's working to oppress us.

01:05:37.040 --> 01:05:38.340
&gt;&gt; [Inaudible] I was
teaching [inaudible].

01:05:38.340 --> 01:05:43.310 position:56%
There's a quote from [inaudible]
and I wanted to [inaudible] response

01:05:43.310 --> 01:05:55.300
about the evolution
of the race poem.

01:05:55.300 --> 01:05:58.780
The quote is, "The
universal is a fantasy.

01:05:58.780 --> 01:06:01.540
But we are captive,
still, to a sensibility

01:06:01.540 --> 01:06:05.030
that champions the universal
while simultaneously defining the

01:06:05.030 --> 01:06:07.160
universal, still, as white.

01:06:07.160 --> 01:06:10.180
We are captive, still, to a
style of championing literature

01:06:10.180 --> 01:06:13.020
that says work by writers
of color succeeds

01:06:13.020 --> 01:06:16.490
when a white person can
nevertheless relate to it --

01:06:16.490 --> 01:06:19.600
that it 'transcends' its category."

01:06:19.600 --> 01:06:25.410
And thinking about the race is
[inaudible] we are changing appears

01:06:25.410 --> 01:06:27.810
how it's viewed [inaudible].

01:06:27.810 --> 01:06:35.790
The sensibility of leaders
is just not [inaudible].

01:06:41.050 --> 01:06:42.350
&gt;&gt; Cathy Park Hong: Well,

01:06:42.350 --> 01:06:44.200
I think the white reader's
sensibility will evolve.

01:06:44.200 --> 01:06:46.410
It's just through his
culture, you know?

01:06:46.410 --> 01:06:49.650
And this is something that
we as editors are doing

01:06:49.650 --> 01:06:52.920
and what I'm trying to do and
what everyone else is doing.

01:06:52.920 --> 01:06:58.930 position:56%
And I think that before there
wasn't -- there was, as we all said,

01:06:58.930 --> 01:07:05.540
just a lot -- a lot less poets of
color, you know, being published.

01:07:05.540 --> 01:07:06.840
Now there are more.

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:09.550
And so, it becomes that.

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:15.640 position:56%
I think in terms of the evolution
of the race poem, what I am starting

01:07:15.640 --> 01:07:16.960
to see I think, you know,

01:07:16.960 --> 01:07:20.500
part of the growing pains that's
happening now is that, you know,

01:07:20.500 --> 01:07:23.160
with the taking also
of the US Census

01:07:23.160 --> 01:07:25.370
and the American demographic
changing,

01:07:25.370 --> 01:07:30.250
the white American is slowly
realizing that they are --

01:07:30.250 --> 01:07:34.400
white is not the universal
category, racial category,

01:07:34.400 --> 01:07:36.160 position:56%
which is very obvious that it's not.

01:07:36.160 --> 01:07:39.140
We're only now really
becoming aware of that.

01:07:39.140 --> 01:07:45.700
And it's also the way the
race poem can also evolve,

01:07:45.700 --> 01:07:47.940
is how a poem by a white
poet is acknowledged

01:07:47.940 --> 01:07:49.580
as a race poem, you know?

01:07:49.580 --> 01:07:53.080
And I am also interested
in that as well.

01:07:53.080 --> 01:07:59.760
Like, for instance, a
lot of the criticism

01:07:59.760 --> 01:08:02.750
about the way we teach
[inaudible], you know,

01:08:02.750 --> 01:08:09.350
writer or even an American
writer or, you know,

01:08:09.350 --> 01:08:10.980
black writers [inaudible].

01:08:10.980 --> 01:08:14.450
What is this poem about?

01:08:14.450 --> 01:08:17.330
What does this poem say
about this demographic

01:08:17.330 --> 01:08:19.880
or this short story
rather than [inaudible]?

01:08:19.880 --> 01:08:24.290
And it's -- of course, we
have to expand and look

01:08:24.290 --> 01:08:25.840
at that poem [inaudible].

01:08:25.840 --> 01:08:28.990
But I'm also interested
actually in turning the table.

01:08:28.990 --> 01:08:32.840
I mean like, okay, here is
a poem by say, for instance,

01:08:32.840 --> 01:08:34.140
Tori Graham [assumed spelling].

01:08:34.140 --> 01:08:35.440
How is this a white poem?

01:08:35.440 --> 01:08:38.700
What does this say sociologically
about white people, you know?

01:08:38.700 --> 01:08:42.590
And I think that's also in certain
ways we're going to acknowledge

01:08:42.590 --> 01:08:45.280
that whiteness is actually
a category rather

01:08:45.280 --> 01:08:49.110
than the universal is to
also kind of look at --

01:08:49.110 --> 01:08:52.130
is to also look at what -- which is
what I think [inaudible] is doing.

01:08:52.130 --> 01:08:58.210
And her textbook is a book
on whiteness, you know?

01:08:58.210 --> 01:08:59.510
So, yeah.

01:08:59.510 --> 01:09:00.810
&gt;&gt; Don Share: Something
in the first part

01:09:00.810 --> 01:09:02.530
of what you're quoting goes back

01:09:02.530 --> 01:09:04.890
to what William Empson
said many decades ago,

01:09:04.890 --> 01:09:09.640
which is that the purpose in a
way of imaginative literature is

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:13.510
to put people in touch with
people whose values are different

01:09:13.510 --> 01:09:14.810
from ours.

01:09:14.810 --> 01:09:16.110
In other words, this idea

01:09:16.110 --> 01:09:19.600
of the universal is just really
dangerous along the lines

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:21.650
that you've all described so well.

01:09:21.650 --> 01:09:23.720
But in terms of teaching,
it's important too

01:09:23.720 --> 01:09:25.430
because I think we see this a lot,

01:09:25.430 --> 01:09:27.900
this thing that poetry's
good for you.

01:09:27.900 --> 01:09:31.770
It's -- we see every day hot
takes in the media about how

01:09:31.770 --> 01:09:33.510
if you read you get
empathy and all this stuff.

01:09:33.510 --> 01:09:35.790
But I think we sort of
know it's not really true,

01:09:35.790 --> 01:09:39.120
or we wouldn't be living in
the world that we're living in.

01:09:39.120 --> 01:09:44.630
But on the other hand, this fear
of difference, whatever it is

01:09:44.630 --> 01:09:49.400
or constitutes or however it can be
described, is something that seems

01:09:49.400 --> 01:09:53.150
to make people very touchy,
and they do terrible things.

01:09:53.150 --> 01:09:56.410
But I think what poetry is
going to do in a way, again,

01:09:56.410 --> 01:09:59.240
that's been described already
is put the different ways

01:09:59.240 --> 01:10:03.150 position:56%
of describing this out there so that
people start to have a handle on it,

01:10:03.150 --> 01:10:08.350
how they imagine what it's like
to be somebody who's in this kind

01:10:08.350 --> 01:10:11.270
of constellation of circumstances.

01:10:11.270 --> 01:10:12.840
But they didn't know that before.

01:10:12.840 --> 01:10:14.770
So you can see poetry doing that.

01:10:14.770 --> 01:10:16.140
The audiences are change --

01:10:16.140 --> 01:10:19.510
the audience for poetry is
changing, which is really great.

01:10:19.510 --> 01:10:24.120
And I think more importantly our
way of teaching not just poetry

01:10:24.120 --> 01:10:26.360
but many things has
to somehow change.

01:10:26.360 --> 01:10:29.330
And our civic culture,
which has to educate people,

01:10:29.330 --> 01:10:31.280
and our politics has to change too.

01:10:31.280 --> 01:10:34.870
It's kind of a tall
order, but it can be done.

01:10:34.870 --> 01:10:39.870
And I mean whether or not it
can be done, it has to be done.

01:10:39.870 --> 01:10:43.160
&gt;&gt; Evie Shockley: Oh, just really
quickly, I think I'm agreeing

01:10:43.160 --> 01:10:46.280
with something you were saying,
but I really wanted to bring

01:10:46.280 --> 01:10:51.100
out the aspect of audience
because there's a way that parts

01:10:51.100 --> 01:10:56.770
of this discussion have
unfolded with a sort

01:10:56.770 --> 01:11:01.720
of de facto white audience
I think in mind.

01:11:01.720 --> 01:11:06.530
And the audience for poetry
had always been as diverse

01:11:06.530 --> 01:11:11.440
as the audience for writers
of poetry and as America.

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:17.650
And it's the prefaces of
Noemi, you know, publishers,

01:11:17.650 --> 01:11:23.700
independent from within different
groups who've been the conduits

01:11:23.700 --> 01:11:29.450
for writers of color to write
to audiences of color for many,

01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:34.250
many years, decades, a century.

01:11:34.250 --> 01:11:39.700
It's the kind of finding a way
to bring not just the writers

01:11:39.700 --> 01:11:43.990
but also the audiences together
that I think opens up a lot.

01:11:43.990 --> 01:11:46.920
And that's what I think
we're all involved.

01:11:51.010 --> 01:11:52.310
&gt;&gt; Female Speaker: [Inaudible].

01:11:52.310 --> 01:11:59.100
Do you as a publisher think and
explore about the difference

01:11:59.100 --> 01:12:02.310
of the [inaudible] between
Latinos and Latin Americans?

01:12:03.860 --> 01:12:05.160 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carmen Gimenez Smith: Absolutely.

01:12:05.160 --> 01:12:08.690
And I mean we also
publish translation,

01:12:08.690 --> 01:12:12.850
a lot of Spanish-speaking poetries.

01:12:12.850 --> 01:12:18.210
And my -- and my culture, my
background is -- I can't escape it.

01:12:18.210 --> 01:12:20.570 position:56%
I can't sort of exist outside of it.

01:12:20.570 --> 01:12:23.320
And so, it absolutely
informs my ethos

01:12:23.320 --> 01:12:26.330
and my politics as
a -- as a publisher.

01:12:26.330 --> 01:12:31.870
And -- but with that in
mind, I love the new.

01:12:31.870 --> 01:12:36.050
I love the transgressive.

01:12:36.050 --> 01:12:39.940
And again, I would say that I
feel like this new generation

01:12:39.940 --> 01:12:43.530
of poets are writing
the most exciting stuff

01:12:43.530 --> 01:12:45.350
about race and identity.

01:12:45.350 --> 01:12:50.600
And so, while I like -- I do --

01:12:50.600 --> 01:12:54.180
I guess it's complicated because
I'm -- right now, I'm editing --

01:12:54.180 --> 01:12:55.910 position:56%
I'm doing some translation of the --

01:12:55.910 --> 01:13:00.910 position:56%
of a countercultural movement in
Peru called Globaca, which was borne

01:13:00.910 --> 01:13:05.950
of the '80s of the kind of
martial law that was instituted

01:13:05.950 --> 01:13:11.720
by President Fujimori at the
time, and I just see so much --

01:13:11.720 --> 01:13:17.390
I also just see so much
similarity between some of the kind

01:13:17.390 --> 01:13:20.410
of political turmoil
that's taking place

01:13:20.410 --> 01:13:23.260
in late 20th century
Latin America and then --

01:13:23.260 --> 01:13:27.110
and then contemporary
American politics

01:13:27.110 --> 01:13:30.760
that the increasing
disparity between classes

01:13:30.760 --> 01:13:36.250
that the horizontal
oppression, the dissatisfaction

01:13:36.250 --> 01:13:39.970
with politics and the government.

01:13:39.970 --> 01:13:44.720
So, you know, I feel like
we're moving into this chapter

01:13:44.720 --> 01:13:47.130
in which we're becoming more
like the rest of the Americas.

01:13:47.130 --> 01:13:51.290
And as a -- as a Latina, as a
woman of South American descent,

01:13:51.290 --> 01:13:53.280
that's really, really
interesting to me.

01:13:53.280 --> 01:13:55.990
And I'm paying attention
to what I know

01:13:55.990 --> 01:13:59.980
about South American
political and literary history.

01:13:59.980 --> 01:14:02.740
I'm just paying attention to
see what things kind of crop

01:14:02.740 --> 01:14:05.260
up that seem similar as well.

01:14:05.260 --> 01:14:06.560
And it's kind of surprising.

01:14:06.560 --> 01:14:09.740
You probably a similar
experience being a translator.

01:14:09.740 --> 01:14:11.040
&gt;&gt; Don Share: Yeah.

01:14:11.040 --> 01:14:12.340
Yeah. Yeah.

01:14:12.340 --> 01:14:13.640
I mean it's funny, isn't it?

01:14:13.640 --> 01:14:16.380
It's like American culture
is finally sort of kicking

01:14:16.380 --> 01:14:19.670
and screaming, being brought
into its world citizenship,

01:14:19.670 --> 01:14:22.210
something to which our
history has sort of --

01:14:22.210 --> 01:14:23.510
&gt;&gt; Carmen Gimenez Smith: Yes.

01:14:23.510 --> 01:14:24.810
&gt;&gt; Don Share: You know?

01:14:24.810 --> 01:14:26.110
Sort of stuck us there,
and what we do

01:14:26.110 --> 01:14:27.850
with it is something you
read about in the news.

01:14:27.850 --> 01:14:33.270
But it's almost like our -- you
know, our existence as a group

01:14:33.270 --> 01:14:38.000
of people coming from all kinds of
different places at every moment.

01:14:38.000 --> 01:14:43.140
It's the movements and migrations
of people in the world that are

01:14:43.140 --> 01:14:45.200
at its peak in recorded history.

01:14:45.200 --> 01:14:49.340
Never before have so many
people been forced to move all

01:14:49.340 --> 01:14:53.080
over the place that in a
way now it's like we're --

01:14:53.080 --> 01:14:54.980
even just that we're
able to have or need

01:14:54.980 --> 01:15:00.380
to have this discussion shows
you that change is happening

01:15:00.380 --> 01:15:02.260
and that it's a -- that
it's a healthy thing.

01:15:02.260 --> 01:15:04.000
But there's a lot of -- you pointed

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:08.160
out specifically danger
in it and invidiousness.

01:15:08.160 --> 01:15:14.070
And, you know, I think that that
is just the price you pay for kind

01:15:14.070 --> 01:15:18.020
of awakening people with language.

